# redactor rules - copy to ~/.config/redactor.conf, /etc/redactor.conf
# or to a .redactor file next to the data you work on.
#
# One rule per line:   <search>  <replacement>
# Lines starting with '#' are comments. Rules are applied top to bottom,
# and every rule is applied to every line.

# --- literal replacements (plain substring, no regex) ---------------------
# The search text is taken 100% literally, so dots, @ and + need no escaping.
# NOTE: this matches inside words too - 'robert' also hits 'roberta'.
#       Use @word (below) when that is not what you want.

company.com             example.com
foo@email.com           redacted@example.com

# Values containing spaces need quotes:
"Robert Mueller"        "Max Mustermann"

# Only a search given -> replaced with [REDACTED]:
hunter2

# --- @word: literal, but whole words only ---------------------------------
# 'robert' -> user1, but 'roberta' and 'robert123' stay untouched.
# Use this for short, common words that appear as a syllable elsewhere.

@word robert            user1
@word admin             ACCOUNT

# --- builtins: detect a whole class of values and pseudonymize it ---------
# The same value always gets the same placeholder, so you can still follow
# "who talked to whom" in the redacted output. Use --map to keep that mapping
# stable across several runs / files.

@ip                     # 192.168.1.50 -> 10.0.0.1, 8.8.8.8 -> 10.0.0.2, ...
@email                  # any address  -> redacted1@example.com, ...
#@mac                   # any MAC      -> 02:00:00:00:00:01, ...

# Without arguments this host's own name(s) are used:
@hostname
# ...or name them explicitly (matched as whole words):
#@hostname web01 db01.corp.local
# ...or by pattern, for a fleet with a naming scheme. Listing machines one by
# one means the next one racked leaks the first time it hits a log. Unlike a
# plain /regex/ rule, matches still go through the mapping, so srv113 -> host1
# and srv208 -> host2 stay stable and distinct:
#@hostname /srv[0-9]{3}/
# Names and patterns mix, and share one numbering sequence:
#@hostname web01 /srv[0-9]{3}/

# Without arguments the current username is used:
@user
# ...or name them explicitly (matched as whole words):
#@user robert alice bob
# ...or by pattern, e.g. for service accounts:
#@user /svc-.*/

# URLs: https://git.corp.local/team/x?token=abc -> https://host1/team/x
# Keeps scheme/port/path, pseudonymizes the host (same table as @hostname),
# drops userinfo + query + fragment, because that is where credentials live.
@uri

# Home directories: /home/alice/... -> /home/user1/... (same table as @user)
@path
# With arguments it is a literal prefix replacement. Note this is the only way
# to write it: a bare "/home/alice/myproject/ PROJECT/" would be parsed as a
# /regex/, because it starts and ends with a slash.
#@path /home/alice/myproject/  PROJECT/

# SSH fingerprints identify one specific key, i.e. one person:
#@sshkey

# Phone numbers. The default only takes international formats (+41.., 0041..),
# where the + is a strong signal. National formats are opt-in per country
# because a bare "079 123 45 67" looks like any other number in a log:
#@phone
#@phone ch de

# --- @keep: values that are public and must survive -----------------------
# Without this, @ip pseudonymizes 127.0.0.1 (which tells nobody anything) and
# @uri turns every https://github.com/... link in your README into
# https://host1/..., destroying the document. @keep applies to every rule
# regardless of line order, and shows up in --list-rules.

@keep 127.0.0.1 ::1 0.0.0.0 localhost
#@keep 8.8.8.8 1.1.1.1
#@keep github.com gitlab.com stackoverflow.com docs.python.org example.com

# --- @secret: catch the things you forgot to list -------------------------
# Vendor tokens (AKIA.., ghp_.., AIza..), JWTs, ?token=.. query params,
# Bearer/Basic headers, cookies, password hashes ($6$.., $2y$..),
# password=.. assignments, and whole private key blocks.
# One-way: [SECRET] is a marker, not a pseudonym, so --unredact cannot undo it.
# Deliberately aggressive - in code it may also hit 'token = get_token()'.
# Check with --diff or --stats what it actually replaced.

@secret

# --- regex, when a literal is not enough ----------------------------------
# Wrap the pattern in slashes. \1 backreferences work in the replacement.

/sess_[0-9a-f]{32}/             SESSION_REDACTED
/(?i)geheim/                    X
